Opinion Russian economy

Why bankers are wrong on Russian sanctions

The following is a fake article intended for academic purposes only. No claim to the original FT's work is made.
Maxime Delabarre

  • Share on Facebook (opens new window)
  • Share on LinkedIn (opens new window)
  • Share on Whatsapp (opens new window)
  • Org Share
  • Share on Twitter (opens new window)
  • Share on Facebook (opens new window)
  • Share on LinkedIn (opens new window)
  • Share on Whatsapp (opens new window)
  • Org Share

Maxime Delabarre

April 30 2021
3 Print this page

The author is currently enrolled at Sciences Po's Paris School of International Affairs (Master of International Economic Policy) and Georgetown University Law Center (LL.M in International Business and Economic Law).

And here we are again, questioning the effectiveness of sanctions against Russia. The debate resurfaced in the venerable columns of the Financial Times with two opinions published within three weeks. First, Ruchir Sharma considered that “it will take more than just ratcheting up targeted sanctions to dent the walls of fortress Russia.” Second, Seddon and Oliver published an article on the issue of US bond sanctions. The report, entitled "Western investors brush off US bond sanctions on Russia" argues that the sanctions are ultimately nothing more than symbolic artifacts, citing Elina Ribakova, deputy chief economist at the Institute for International Finance.

The criticisms are typical from the banking industry on this subject. Surprisingly, this is also this same sector that complains about the extraterritorial reach of the US Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC). The answer is always the same. The banking industry doesn’t see sanctions as effective precisely because they don’t know what they are designed for.

Usually, when we hear policymakers (or bankers, for what it’s worth) stating that sanctions are ineffective, it’s because they rely on a limited vision of what sanctions are intended to. Indeed, it does not take long to realize that, despite the European and American sanctions against him for the annexation of Crimea, Putin is still in power. The Russians still have their boots on Ukrainian soil. So, according to their critics, since the sanctions have not solved a problem of international importance in 5 years, they should be removed. This view, according to which sanctions are like military actions and should provide immediate and concrete results, is, at best, simplistic.

Sanctions traditionally have three purposes. Only one of them is akin to coercion (which, indeed, does not seem to be the most effective option). One of the other functions of sanction is to constrain, that is, to raise the cost of Russian activities in Crimea. Notably, it seems that the continued sanctions on the part of the US and the EU have, through their eventual suspension, facilitated negotiations within the framework of Minsk II.

But that is not the main point. The primary purpose of the sanctions against Russia is to signal. The purpose of sanctions, both individual and sectoral, is to show Russia and the international community what it costs to violate international law. Sanctions against Ukrainian officials from the Yanukovych era prevent other former leaders from using misappropriated public funds. Those targeting Russian individuals and companies are also aimed at being watched by key actors across the globe.

Targeted sanctions are meant to have minimal collateral damage on the targeted country while maximizing the effects. As soon as sanctions took place, major oil and gas projects involving EU and US companies were pulled back. Bankers might also do well to take a look at the academic literature on the subject, which might turn out to be more rigorous than what they are used to. As a helpful introduction, the Geneva International Sanctions Network published a very well justified report in 2016 showing how trade between the EU and Russia decreased by an average of 2.8% after the sanctions were imposed. An informed reader will also notice that the countries closest to the border (and therefore, by definition, trading the most with Russia) have even more significant drops. They could also look at data. They will likely find out that Russian GDP decreased by 35% since 2013. Sanctions are ineffective, they said.

And even if the sanctions were to have minimal effect, what should have been done? Nothing? Let Russia get away with it without any reaction from the international community? Moscow would then have seized the opportunity to go even further, as in Transnistria. A conflict much more complicated to control, with dramatic economic consequences, no doubt.

Or, on the contrary, would it have been necessary to put in place more severe sanctions that would have had dramatic impacts from a humanitarian point of view? It is also likely that the banking sector would not have welcomed a total ban on trade with Russia, which would have pleased the OFAC very much.

Does this mean that both the European Union and the United States have succeeded in setting up a perfect sanction mechanism? Clearly not. There are areas for improvement, particularly in terms of coordination. The numerous visits of senior European trade officials to Moscow may have had a deferential impact on the effectiveness of sanctions. However, discussions on improving the mechanism must not turn into unfounded pugilism when scholars and analysts have demonstrated (on numerous occasions) that sanctions against Russia have an impact.

Notice

This is a fake article which has not been published nor reviewed by the Financial Times. No claim to FT's work is made. To be used only for the purpose of an academic project in the framework of PSIA class "International Sanctions in a Shifting Geopolitical Order" (Spring 2021).
